    <p><strong>Abstract.</strong> Mountrichas et al. (2026) combine XMM-Newton X-ray spectroscopy with SDSS optical spectroscopy for 241 X-ray AGN at z &lt; 1.9 to investigate the link between optical AGN classification and X-ray absorption. They identify two mismatched populations: broad-line AGN with X-ray absorption (BLAbs) and narrow-line AGN unobscured in X-rays (NLUnabs), suggesting that AGN obscuration arises from multi-scale gas/dust distributions, not orientation alone.</p>

    <h2>Key findings</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Optical-X-ray agreement:</strong> ~70% of sources (172/241) show agreement between optical classification and X-ray absorption properties.</li>
      <li><strong>BLAbs population:</strong> 11 broad-line AGN with X-ray absorption; elevated gas-to-dust ratios suggest dust-free or host-scale absorbers.</li>
      <li><strong>NLUnabs population:</strong> 58 narrow-line AGN unobscured in X-rays; ~50% assigned type-1 properties by SED fitting; higher Balmer decrements than standard NL AGN.</li>
      <li><strong>Host property contrasts:</strong> NLUnabs resemble BL AGN in SFR and accretion efficiency; NL AGN reside in quiescent hosts with lower star formation.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Implications</h2>
    <p>Obscuration in AGN arises from multi-scale gas and dust distributions, not orientation alone. Mismatched populations complicate AGN demographic interpretation in large surveys (Euclid, LSST/VRO).</p>

